  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2024 in the <em>Journal of Translation Studies</em>, Fran\u00e7ois Massion's article on the transformation of terminology theory and practice in the age of AI has accumulated 5 citations within its first year, placing it in the top 2% of similarly aged works by citation volume. Its citing community spans applied linguistics, translation technology, and institutional terminology management, signalling early but substantive uptake across a focused disciplinary cluster.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Massion's article addresses a timely question at the intersection of computational linguistics and terminological theory: how do AI-driven tools \u2014 particularly large language models and generative systems \u2014 reshape the foundational assumptions and practical workflows of terminology work? The piece draws on epistemological and linguistic frameworks alongside natural language processing perspectives, positioning itself as both a theoretical intervention and a practitioner-facing analysis. Its 28-page scope allows for substantive engagement with questions of conceptual stability, term extraction, and the evolving role of human expertise when automated systems can generate and manage terminological content at scale.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article's citation trajectory is notable for a work published in early 2024: three citations appeared in 2025 and one further citation is already recorded for 2026, suggesting sustained rather than purely reactive engagement. Citing works appear in <em>Lebende Sprachen</em>, <em>Tradum\u00e0tica: tecnologies de la traducci\u00f3</em>, and the German-language edited volume series <em>Studien zu Fach, Sprache und Kultur</em>, venues that collectively represent the core readership of applied translation and language technology research in the German-speaking world and beyond. Notably, Tanja Wissik of the Austrian Academy of Sciences has cited the work in two separate publications \u2014 one empirical study on terminology professionals in institutional settings and one book chapter on the impacts of AI on institutional terminology work \u2014 underscoring the article's relevance to research examining real-world professional practice.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Thematically, the citing literature concentrates on professional workflows and competence development in AI-augmented language industries, with Ralph Kr\u00fcger's 2025 article in <em>Lebende Sprachen</em> (itself already accumulating 4 citations) exploring competence frameworks for generative AI adoption in language industry contexts. This suggests that Massion's contribution is functioning as a conceptual anchor for a small but active community of scholars working on the human-AI interface in specialized language work. The geographic spread of citing institutions \u2014 Germany, Austria, and China \u2014 indicates early cross-regional relevance, though the community remains concentrated in European applied linguistics and translation studies.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Beyond direct citations, the article carries a strong alignment with the UN Sustainable Development Goal of Quality Education (SDG 4), reflecting its potential utility in framing curricula and professional development programmes for translators and terminologists navigating AI-transformed workplaces. It has also been indexed on the publisher's open-access platform, broadening discoverability. While social media and broader online discourse have not yet registered measurable activity around this work, the citation-based evidence positions it as an early reference point in an emerging scholarly conversation \u2014 one likely to grow as AI's integration into language industries deepens and the field seeks theoretically grounded accounts of that transformation.</p>",
